        "$:/plugins/twpub/6d09b81e32b0d4bf/text/000000297": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/6d09b81e32b0d4bf/text/000000297",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-6d09b81e32b0d4bf-0fdc9a twpub-6d09b81e32b0d4bf-c3c16f twpub-6d09b81e32b0d4bf-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"footnotes\"><div class=\"footnote\"><p><a></a><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/6d09b81e32b0d4bf/text/000000257\"><span class=\"label\">[P]</span></$link> &quot;The Dying Negro,&quot; a poem originally published in 1773. Perhaps it may not be deemed impertinent here to add, that this elegant and pathetic little poem was occasioned, as appears by the advertisement prefixed to it, by the following incident. &quot;A black, who, a few days before had ran away from his master, and got himself christened, with intent to marry a white woman his fellow-servant, being taken and sent on board a ship in the Thames, took an opportunity of shooting himself through the head.&quot;</p></div></div></div>"
        },
